Heisenberg XY model

The quantum Heisenberg XY model is given by $$H=\sum_{i} J_{i}((1+\gamma)\sigma_{i}^x \sigma_{i+1}^x + (1-\gamma)\sigma_{i}^y \sigma_{i+1}^y) + \sum_{i}B_{i}\sigma_{i}^z,$$ where $J_i$ is the pair-wise antiferromagnetic exchange and $B_i$ is the strength of the on-site magnetic field. The parameter $\gamma$ induces an anisotropic interaction between directions $x$ and $y$. In the case of $\gamma=0$, we have the so-called XX model $$H=\sum_{i} J_{i}(\sigma_{i}^x \sigma_{i+1}^x + \sigma_{i}^y \sigma_{i+1}^y) + \sum_{i}B_{i}\sigma_{i}^z$$
